Two choriambic pentameters enclosing a tetrameter, followed by two iambic hypermetra. The close oi the first iambic hypermetron is marked by hiatus in the ode and by syllaba anceps in the antode. The contrast in form between the iambic hypermetra is admirably adapted to heighten the comic effect of the sentiment. The triseme syllable at the beginning oi an iambic dipody (10, 12) is now clearly established by the authority of Aristoxenus.1
